<br>
Starting at level 35 (about the level mobs start riposting and when warriors get riposte) a warrior should have a 20 percent chance of blocking a mob's riposte, at level 30 this should be increased to about 35 percent, at level 40, you should be able to block 50 percent, at level 50, 65 percent, and at level 60, 85 percent of ripostes should be able to be blocked by a warrior.  Enrage should still work as it does and riposte blocking should not be affected by this for a number of reasons.  <br>
<br>
When a warrior does successfully block a mob's riposte, he should be given a chance to land a disorienting blow (the mob is disoriented after having his riposte blocked) that does around 200-300 damage (this will most likely need to be tweaked) at level 60 and includes an innate stun that lasts around 3-4 seconds (Stun subject to resist this being so you can't stun the AoW etc..).  This would decrease the amount of damage a warrior takes and would increase the warriors DPS through a RP perspective.  As for AA abilities, Double Riposte will still only allow 1 chance at a disorienting blow and a new AA should be added which allows warriors to have a 2, 5, and 10 percent increase (max 95 percent at level 60) of blocking a riposte.<br>
<br>
In a group setting, this would help warriors become the first choice for a MT, and during soloing, would increase the warrior's ability to solo.  Assuming the new heals for druids and shamans goes live, this would allow a warrior do be more easily grouped with a group with a druid or shaman healer than a Paladin or SK MT as the warrior would be taking less damage.  As warriors SHOULD be your MT, this will only affect a warrior that IS your MT.<br>
<br>
I have a level 60 warrior and play from MT'ing for exp groups ranging from Sebilis to Cazic Thule to MT'ing luclin mobs like the High Priest of Ssraeszha, Arch Lich Rhag`Zadune and know that this WOULD help warriors through DPS and tanking abilities without being overpowering.  This would also give warrior's something new which we seem to completely lack. <br>
<br>
